# Extension Ontology Authoring

When working on extension ontology TTL files, follow these patterns.

## File Structure

Each extension should have separate OWL and SHACL files:
- `myext.ttl` — OWL class and property definitions
- `myext-shapes.ttl` — SHACL NodeShape constraints
- `myext-exemplar.ttl` — example instance data for validation testing

## Class Definition Pattern

Every extension class must subclass an existing UCO/CASE class:

```turtle
myext:MyClass
    a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf uco-core:UcoObject ;
    rdfs:label "MyClass"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "Description of what this class represents."@en .
```

## SHACL Shape Pattern

Each class needs a corresponding NodeShape:

```turtle
myext:MyClass-shape
    a sh:NodeShape ;
    sh:targetClass myext:MyClass ;
    sh:property [
        sh:path myext:myProperty ;
        sh:datatype xsd:string ;
        sh:minCount 1 ;
        sh:maxCount 1 ;
    ] .
```

## Scaffolding Typed Classes

After defining the TTL, generate starter code for any language:

```bash
case-uco-generate scaffold \
  --extension myext.ttl myext-shapes.ttl \
  --lang python \
  --output-dir ./generated/
```

## Validation

Validate exemplar data against the extension shapes:

```bash
case_validate --built-version case-1.4.0 \
  --ontology-graph myext.ttl \
  --ontology-graph myext-shapes.ttl \
  myext-exemplar.ttl
```

See the `extensions/toolcap/` directory for a complete validated example.
